BT 0 g /F2 20 Tf 162.0 720 Td (Chapter 2: The Triassic Period) Tj ET
q 0.5 G 1 w 72 710 m 540 710 l S Q
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 680 Td (The time machine landed with a THUD. Leo and Luna stepped out into a hot, dry world.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 664 Td ('Welcome to the Triassic Period - 230 million years ago!' the machine announced.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 648 Td (The landscape looked different: all the continents were joined in one supercontinent!) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 632 Td (Small dinosaurs, only about the size of dogs, scurried through the ferns.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 616 Td ('These are the FIRST dinosaurs!' Luna pointed. 'They are so small!') Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 600 Td ('But give them 165 million years,' Leo smiled, 'and they will rule the whole planet!') Tj ET
BT 0 g /F2 13 Tf 72 564 Td (THE SCIENCE: THE TRIASSIC WORLD) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 544 Td (The Triassic Period lasted from 252 to 201 million years ago.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 528 Td (All continents were joined in one supercontinent called Pangaea.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 512 Td (The first dinosaurs appeared about 230 million years ago - they were small!) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 496 Td (Early dinosaurs like Eoraptor were only about 3 feet long and walked on two legs.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 480 Td (Other animals lived alongside them: early mammals \(tiny!\), crocodile ancestors, and more.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 464 Td (The climate was mostly hot and dry with no polar ice caps.) Tj ET
q 0.92 g 67 374 478 89 re f Q
BT 0 g /F2 11 Tf 77 433 Td (SCIENCE FACT BOX) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 10 Tf 82 413 Td (* Pangaea means 'all lands' in Greek - it was one giant landmass!) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 10 Tf 82 395 Td (* The first dinosaurs were not the biggest - they had to compete with other reptiles.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 10 Tf 82 377 Td (* Dinosaurs became dominant after a mass extinction wiped out their competitors.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F2 11 Tf 72 344 Td (TRY THIS!) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 10 Tf 82 328 Td (Cut out the continents from a map and try to fit them together like a puzzle - that is Pangaea!) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F2 11 Tf 72 308 Td (THINK ABOUT IT:) Tj ET
BT 0.2 g /F4 10 Tf 82 292 Td (If all continents were once joined, how did they move apart? What force moved them?) Tj ET

endstream
