BT 0 g /F2 20 Tf 166.8 720 Td (Chapter 4: The Fierce Hunters) Tj ET
q 0.5 G 1 w 72 710 m 540 710 l S Q
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 680 Td (The twins traveled to the Cretaceous Period - 68 million years ago.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 664 Td (THUMP. THUMP. THUMP. The ground shook with heavy footsteps.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 648 Td (Through the trees appeared the most famous dinosaur of all: Tyrannosaurus Rex!) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 632 Td (It was 40 feet long with teeth the size of bananas and jaws that could crush bone!) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 616 Td ('RUN!' Leo yelled. But the T. Rex was not interested in them - it was chasing prey!) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 600 Td (They watched from behind a fallen log as the mighty hunter sprinted past at 20 mph.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F2 13 Tf 72 564 Td (THE SCIENCE: CARNIVOROUS DINOSAURS) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 544 Td (T. Rex: 40 ft long, 12 ft tall at the hip, 9 tons - the apex predator!) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 528 Td (Its bite force was 12,800 pounds - strong enough to crush a car!) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 512 Td (T. Rex had excellent eyesight and could see better than a hawk.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 496 Td (Velociraptor: smaller \(6 ft\) but hunted in packs and was incredibly smart.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 480 Td (Spinosaurus: possibly the largest carnivorous dinosaur \(50+ ft\), ate fish!) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 464 Td (Carnivores had sharp, curved teeth for tearing meat \(unlike flat herbivore teeth\).) Tj ET
q 0.92 g 67 374 478 89 re f Q
BT 0 g /F2 11 Tf 77 433 Td (SCIENCE FACT BOX) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 10 Tf 82 413 Td (* T. Rex arms were only about 3 feet long - but could still lift 400 pounds each!) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 10 Tf 82 395 Td (* T. Rex could eat up to 500 pounds of meat in a single bite.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 10 Tf 82 377 Td (* Real Velociraptors were only about 6 feet long and had feathers \(not like in movies!\).) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F2 11 Tf 72 344 Td (TRY THIS!) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 10 Tf 82 328 Td (Compare your teeth in a mirror: flat ones for grinding \(herbivore\) and pointed ones for tearing \(carnivore\)!) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F2 11 Tf 72 308 Td (THINK ABOUT IT:) Tj ET
BT 0.2 g /F4 10 Tf 82 292 Td (Was T. Rex a hunter, a scavenger, or both? What evidence would tell us?) Tj ET

endstream
